<p class="content__abstract">
  This article introduces HTML, the language of the web. Read it to learn what HTML tags are and which ones to use, when.
</p>

<p>Your website is looking pretty bare at the moment. You need to write some code! You will use HTML to structure your web page.</p>

<h2 id="html-tags">HTML tags</h2>
<p><a href="glossary#html">HTML</a> is composed of HTML tags that go at the start and the finish of the content that you want to mark up. They come in two parts: an opening HTML tag such as <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;p&gt;</code>, and a closing HTML tag such as <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;/p&gt;</code>, (notice the <code class="highlighter-rouge">/</code> before the <code class="highlighter-rouge">p</code>).</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>It’s a bit like the old advice for giving a speech: “Tell ’em what you’re going to tell ’em; tell ’em; tell ’em what you’ve told ’em”. Or the age-old advice for good storytelling – have a beginning, a middle, and an end:</p>

  <p><code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;p&gt;</code> means there’s a paragraph coming up.</p>

  <p>Then there’s a paragraph.</p>

  <p>Then <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;/p&gt;</code> means that we just had a paragraph, and now it’s over.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Here’s a list of HTML tags. You will use them to tell the browser how it should structure your page.</p>

<p><strong>Paragraph</strong></p>

<p>Here is an example of paragraph <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;p&gt;</code> <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;/p&gt;</code> tags in action:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;p&gt;</span>
    An anthologie of fine stories
    inspir’d by the Bard of Stratford and the Lovecraftian Mythos
  <span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Which display in a browser as:</p>

<div class="display-box">
  <p class="display">
    An anthologie of fine stories
    inspir’d by the Bard of Stratford
    and the Lovecraftian Mythos
  </p>
</div>

<p><strong>Strong</strong></p>

<p>Here is an example of strong <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;strong&gt;</code> <code class="highlighter-rouge">&lt;/strong&gt;</code> tags in action:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;p&gt;</span>
    An anthologie of fine stories
    inspir’d by the <span class="nt">&lt;strong&gt;</span>Bard of Stratford<span class="nt">&lt;/strong&gt;</span>
    and the Lovecraftian Mythos
  <span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Which display in a browser as:</p>

<div class="display-box">
  <p class="display">
    An anthologie of fine stories
    inspir’d by the <strong>Bard of Stratford</strong>
    and the Lovecraftian Mythos
  </p>
</div>

<p><strong>Headings</strong></p>

<p>Here is an example of heading tags in action:</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;h3&gt;</span>Shakespeare vs Cthulhu<span class="nt">&lt;/h3&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;h4&gt;</span>An Anthologie<span class="nt">&lt;/h4&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Which display in a browser as:</p>

<div class="display-box">
  <div class="display">
    <h3>Shakespeare vs Cthulhu</h3>
    <h4>An Anthologie</h4>
  </div>
</div>

<p><strong>List</strong></p>

<p>Usually interpreted as a bulleted list e.g.</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;ul&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;li&gt;</span>Publisher: Snowbooks<span class="nt">&lt;/li&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;li&gt;</span>Published on: 2 August 2016<span class="nt">&lt;/li&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;li&gt;</span>ISBN: 978-1-909679-86-3<span class="nt">&lt;/li&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;/ul&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<div class="display-box">
  <div class="display">
    <ul>
      <li>Publisher: Snowbooks</li>
      <li>Published on: 2 August 2016</li>
      <li>ISBN: 978-1-909679-86-3</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</div>

<p><strong>Division</strong></p>

<p>A division or section of the page.</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;div&gt;</span>
    <span class="nt">&lt;p&gt;</span>
      An anthologie of fine stories inspir’d
      by the <span class="nt">&lt;strong&gt;</span>Bard of Stratford<span class="nt">&lt;/strong&gt;</span> and the Lovecraftian Mythos
    <span class="nt">&lt;/p&gt;</span>
  <span class="nt">&lt;/div&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p><strong>Image</strong></p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-html" data-lang="html">  <span class="nt">&lt;img</span> <span class="na">src=</span><span class="s">'/assets/images/cover.png'</span> <span class="na">alt=</span><span class="s">'Shakespeare vs Cthulhu cover image'</span><span class="nt">&gt;</span></code></pre></figure>

<p>Code which points to a file location of an image to display. <code class="highlighter-rouge">src</code> means source – the file location. <code class="highlighter-rouge">alt</code> means alternative text – vital for accessibility.</p>

<div class="display-box">
  <div class="display">
     <img src="/assets/images/cover.png" alt="Shakespeare vs Cthulhu cover image" />
  </div>
</div>

<h2 id="html-vs-css">HTML vs CSS</h2>
<p>HTML provides the structure of a web page; later on, we’ll use CSS to provide the visual layout. This is an important point. A piece of text may be classed as a paragraph using HTML. That is a different to saying that the paragraph style should be Lucida Sans, 14pt, dark grey, and indented 5px on each side. You will provide such stylistic instructions in CSS.</p>

<h2 id="what-youve-learned">What you’ve learned</h2>

<ul>
  <li>There are opening and closing HTML tags.</li>
  <li>HTML structures web pages; CSS styles them.</li>
</ul>

